  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Integrated WASH and FSL Response for IDPs, returnees and host communities in Al Abbassiya and Abu Karsho</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">An inter-agency assessment conducted by CAFOD, in collaboration with ASSIST, SIDO and UPO revealed existence of widespread FSL and WASH gaps and needs for IDPs, returnees and host communities in Abu Kershola, Al Abbassiya and Al Qoz localities. The assessment was conducted in Al Qoz locality (Kurkurra and EL-Dubaibat south villages) on 27th &#x2013; 30th August; Al Abbassiya locality (Gardoud Nyama and Banet villages) on 1st &#x2013; 4th September and in Abu-Kershola locality (Alfaid and Khor Eldalaib villages) on 6th &#x2013; 8th September 2019. The assessment established that affected populations continued to face critical gaps in accessing food, water and had no reliable sources of livelihoods. High number of IDPs, returnees and host community populations were food insecure (had no stored grain food; poor status of animal health), lacked sufficient agricultural inputs, had no access to reliable sources of livelihoods (most had sold out livelihood assets such as livestock, household items and farming tools), and lacked money to purchase farm inputs/tools from the markets. 
The overall objective of the project is to provide lifesaving Water Sanitation and Hygiene (WASH), Food Security and Livelihoods (FSL) services and facilities to at least 12,844 people (approximately 2570 HHs) in Al Abbassiya and Abu Kershola localities. Affected population to be targeted by the project will be Internally Displaced Persons (IDPs), returnees and host communities.
The following are the expected project outcomes: 
1. Increased capacity of at least 12,844 people to sustainably access quality and sufficient clean water
2 Increased target communities&apos; knowledge and skills on safe sanitation and hygiene practices
3. Increased capacity of at least 1000 HHs to access agricultural inputs and services
4. Increased capacity of at least 1000 HHs on household food availability through reduction of farm and post-harvest losses</narrative>
  </description>
